Germany's DAX Index Declines, Erasing Weekly Gain; Lufthansa Shares Drop

-- B y   J u l i e   C r u z
-- 
2011-03-04T17:05:48Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-04/german-stocks-fluctuate-after-u-s-jobs-data-hannover-re-munich-re-gain.html
German stocks retreated, with the
benchmark  DAX Index (DAX)  erasing its weekly advance, as the oil price
surged amid concern political unrest will spread to the Arabian
peninsula.    Deutsche Lufthansa AG (LHA)  declined 2 percent as investors
speculated fuel costs will rise.  Kabel Deutschland Holding AG (KD8) 
slumped 3.8 percent after its biggest shareholder sold a stake.  The DAX fell 0.7 percent to 7,178.9 at the 5:30 p.m. close
in Frankfurt, for a weekly retreat of 0.1 percent. The gauge has
declined 3.3 percent since peaking at a 2 1/2-year high on Feb.
18. The broader HDAX Index retreated 0.6 percent today.  The DAX erased an earlier gain of 1.2 percent after U.S.
government data signaled that growth in wages may fail to keep
up with surging energy prices.  “Ahead of the weekend many are probably worried that
things might just get worse,” said Markus Huber, head of German
sales trading at ETX Capital in  London . “Markets haven’t been
that solid anyway after the non-farm data and investors are
looking for an excuse.”  Crude rose to a 29-month high in New York on concern unrest
in Libya will spread to other Middle East oil producers, curbing
exports, and as a falling U.S. jobless rate signaled that fuel
demand will climb.  U.S. Jobs  U.S. employers added 192,000 workers in February, amid an
improving economy and more seasonable weather, a government
report showed today. The  unemployment rate  unexpectedly declined
to 8.9 percent. The gain in payrolls followed a 63,000 increase
in January and compared with the 196,000 median estimate of
economists surveyed by Bloomberg News.  Average hourly earnings were unchanged, the data showed.
Economists in a Bloomberg survey had forecast 0.2 percent
growth.  Lufthansa, Europe’s second-biggest airline, tumbled 2
percent to 14.50 euros.  Daimler AG (DAI) , the world’s second-biggest
maker of luxury cars, lost 1.9 percent to 48.24 euros.    Kabel Deutschland  sank 3.8 percent to 38 euros as Cable
Holding SA sold 20 million shares in the company to
institutional investors for 38 euros each.  To contact the reporters on this story:
